Earl "Bubba" Kidder, Jr, 39, is missing. He went fishing with two friends on March 28, 2010 and phoned saying the fishing was going well. However, he never showed up the next morning to attend with his ill mom to a physician appointment. He has not been seen since. His family, children and friends are extremely worried.
His sister says he was picked up by a friend for a weekend fishing trip in the Sherburne Wildlife Management Area.
The car his friend picked him up in, was found extensively burned in Sherburne by Wildlife and Fisheries agents. We're told detectives spent the day questioning the two people who were fishing with Bubba before he vanished.
The missing man's fishing companions state that they have no idea what happened to him. Bubba is 6'2" tall, weighing about 195 pounds with brown hair and eyes. He has a dimpled chin and a large scar on his right arm near his elbow.

Originally Webster Parish Sheriff's Office case # 00-004907

 A missing-person case involving a Bossier City businesswoman who disappeared 18 years ago has been reopened by Louisiana State Police. The case involves the disappearance of Wilda Cross, a record-setting competitive water skier who lived in Webster Parish and operated Cross jewelry store in Bossier City with her husband.  State Police took over the investigation as a "cold case" sent to them by the Webster Parish Sheriff's Department. The Crosses were living in Sibley when she disappeared on March 23, 1992.  "The last time she was seen was 7:30 that morning, and hasn't been seen since," State Police Trooper Phillip Krouse said. "It's almost like she fell off the face of the earth." Cross had been gone for three days when her husband told her family she had disappeared, Krouse said. The family contacted authorities.  Krouse said Mrs. Cross has not contacted family members or friends since March 23, 1992.  He's asking for friends with information about Cross to contact State Police.

Brown's sister told authorities that Brown got into the vehicle with the couple after the man and woman offered to watch her. The vehicle then left with Remona Brown, who has not been seen or heard from since, police said, despite a search of the house and surrounding area.

The vehicle belonging to McAlister is a white 2011 Toyota Tundra bearing Louisiana license plate B658023.  The truck appeared to have gone off the roadway and had minor damage.  The truck was unoccupied.  The Calcasieu Parish Sheriff's Office received the missing person's report on August 5th and discovered that his vehicle had been involved in an accident in Cameron Parish and had been towed.  McAlister was last seen in the late hours of August 3rd.
Charles McAlister is a 71-year-old white male with gray hair and brown eyes.  He is approximately 5'10" tall and weighs 155 lbs.  He was last seen wearing a white sports cap which had the following wording: Island Moorings Yacht Club and Marina, Port Aransas, Texas, light grey t-shirt, light colored denim blue jeans, white New Balance Brand tennis shoes, and glasses.  He does have a mustache.  The Calcasieu Parish Sheriff's Office is asking for the public's assistance in locating McAlister.  If anyone sees him or knows of his whereabouts, please contact the Calcasieu Parish Sheriff's Office at 491-3605.
